<H1>Graphics (HIGZ and HPLOT)
<H2 SUBJECT='HPLOT, HIGZ and local graphics package'>HPLOT, HIGZ and local graphics package
<I1>HIGZ
<I1>HPLOT
<P>Graphics input/output in PAW is handled by the two packages
HPLOT (Histograms PLOTting)
and HIGZ (High level Interface to Graphics and Zebra).
HIGZ is the basic graphics system of
PAW interfacing the local graphics package while HPLOT,
sitting on top of HIGZ, is used
for plotting HBOOK objects (Histograms, Ntuples, etc.). The figure below
shows the hierarchy between HPLOT, HIGZ and the local basic
graphics package (GKS, DI3000, X Windows, etc.).
<FIG PLACE=INLINE FRAME=NONE ID=GRAPH1 WIDTH=COLUMN>
<FIGCAP>HPLOT and HIGZ in PAW
<ARTWORK NAME=GRAPH1 DEPTH=135mm ALIGN=CENTER>
</FIG>
Graphics could be produced in PAW either directly by HIGZ commands
or by HPLOT commands. In both cases,
all the graphics is under the control of HIGZ.
Two distinct modes are available in HIGZ: one is purely graphics (the <HP2>G</HP2> mode)
interfacing the local graphics package, and the second (the <HP2>Z</HP2> mode)
allows the management of the HIGZ structures (pictures).
As an example, the simple PAW
command <XPH>HISTOGRAM/PLOT</XPH> is handled at the different levels as follows:
<DL TSIZE=15 COMPACT>
<DT>PAW Level
<DD>HISTOGRAM/PLOT ID
<DT>HPLOT Level
<DD>Takes care of ZONE, SET, OPTION, etc.
<DT>HIGZ Level
<DD>Windows and Viewport, Axis, Boxes, Histogram, Text and Attributes
<DT>Basic graphics
<DD>Line, Text, Attributes, etc.
</DL>
<?.CC 25>
<H2 SUBJECT='The metafiles'>The metafiles
<I1>metafile
<P>Metafiles are text files used as device independent sources of graphics output
for printers of different type. PAW is able to produce two types of metafiles.
<P>The first one is the local graphics package metafile (for example a GKS metafile).
This file is produced by the local graphics package and it usually needs
a special interpreter to be sent to the printers.
For example, at CERN, the GKS metafile (workstation type <XPH>4</XPH>)
must be printed with <XPH>gkscp, gksvt, gkstv </XPH> or <XPH>gksx87</XPH>.
<P>The second type of metafile is directly produced
by HIGZ and is independent from the basic graphics package
used. This type of metafile is a PostScript metafile
(workstation type <HP2>-111</HP2>: portrait; <HP2>-112</HP2>: landscape)
and could be sent directly to a PostScript printer
(at CERN GKS metafiles type
<HP2>12201</HP2> and <HP2>12202</HP2> could be also used
to produce PostScript metafiles).
<P>The command <XPH>GRAPHICS/METAFILE LUN METAFL</XPH> is designed
to produce metafiles. <XPH>LUN</XPH> is the logical unit number of an open
FORTRAN file and <XPH>METAFL</XPH> the metafile type.
For example, the following four commands
will produce a HIGZ/PostScript metafile with the name "PAW.PS"
containing the graphics representation of histogram number <XPH>10</XPH>:
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>FORTRAN/FILE 66 PAW.PS</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>GRAPHICS/META 66 -111</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>HISTO/PLOT 10</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>FORTRAN/CLOSE 66</HP3>
</XMP>
<H2 ID=H2HIGZP SUBJECT='The HIGZ pictures'>The HIGZ pictures
<I1>picture
<P>The HIGZ pictures have three main goals:
<UL>
<LI>To store the HIGZ graphics primitives and attributes
in a ZEBRA structure in memory in order to display them later.
<LI>To be stored in direct access files (in a very compact way), in order to build a picture data base.
<LI>To be modified with the graphics editor.
</UL>
<H3 ID=H3PICT>Pictures in memory
<I1>IZPICT
<P>The general command to manage pictures in memory is:
<XPH>PICTURE/IZPICT</XPH>.
This command has two parameters:
<DL TSIZE=8 COMPACT>
<DT>PNAME
<DD>Picture name:
<DL TSIZE=4 COMPACT>
<DT>CH
<DD>Character string specifying picture name (must begin with a letter)
<DT>N
<DD>Picture number as displayed by <XPH>PICT/LIST</XPH>.
<DT>*
<DD>All pictures in memory.
<DT>' '
<DD>A blank indicates the current picture.
</DL>
<DT>CHOPT
<DD>Option value:
<DL COMPACT TSIZE=4>
<DT>D
<DD>Display the picture PNAME.
<DT>F
<DD>First picture in memory becomes the current picture.
<DT>L
<DD>List pictures in memory.
<DT>AL
<DD>Give a full listing of the pictures in memory.
<DT>M
<DD>Make a new picture in memory with the name PNAME.
<DT>P
<DD>Print the contents of the picture PNAME.
<DT>C
<DD>Picture PNAME becomes the current picture.
<DT>N
<DD>Next picture in memory becomes the current picture.
<DT>S
<DD>Scratch picture PNAME from memory.
</DL>
</DL>
<P>In addition, more simple and mnemonic commands are available:
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>PICT/CREATE PNAME</HP3>           | Create a picture in memory
PAW > <HP3>PICT/LIST</HP3>                   | List pictures in memory
 1: PNAME <-- Current Picture
</XMP>
<I1>current picture
<?.cc 50>
<P>The last created picture in memory is called the <HP2>current</HP2> picture. All graphics
primitives (line, text, histogram, etc.) produced by PAW commands will be stored
in this picture if it is <HP2>active</HP2>, i.e. if the mode <HP2>Z</HP2> is on.
<I1>SWITCH Z
<I1>mode Z
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>SWITCH Z</HP3>                     | Switch Z mode on
PAW > <HP3>PICT/LIST</HP3>
 1: PNAME <-- Current Picture (Active)
</XMP>
<I1>active picture
Note that the command <XPH>PICTURE/CREATE</XPH> will switch automatically
the <HP2>Z</HP2> on.
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>PICT/PLOT PNAME</HP3>
</XMP>
will display the picture PNAME. If the picture PNAME is not in memory and if
the current working directory (as given by <XPH>CDIR</XPH>) is a picture file, PAW will try
to take this picture from the file before displaying it.
<P>HIGZ pictures can be created automatically by HPLOT via the command:
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>OPTION ZFL</HP3>
</XMP>
<I1>ZFL (option)
If this command has been typed, each new plot produced by HPLOT will result in a
HIGZ
picture created in memory. The following example shows how for each
<XPH>HIST/PLOT ID</XPH> command a new HIGZ picture is created with an automatic naming:
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>HIST/PLOT 10</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>HIST/PLOT 110</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>HIST/PLOT 20</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>PICT/LIST</HP3>
 1: PICT1
 2: PICT2
 3: PICT3 <-- Current Picture (Active)
</XMP>
A similar command is given by:
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>OPTION ZFL1</HP3>
</XMP>
<I1>ZFL1 (option)
which works exactly like <XPH>OPTION ZFL</XPH> except that only the last
created picture is kept in memory. For example, should we have typed <XPH>OPTION ZFL1</XPH>
instead of <XPH>OPTION ZFL</XPH> in the example above, the result would be:
<XMP>
PAW > <HP3>PICT/LIST</HP3>
 1: PICT3 <-- Current Picture (Active)
</XMP>
The following example is a useful macro showing how to use the HIGZ pictures
(via <XPH>OPTION ZFL1</XPH>) and the metafiles in order to produce a hard copy
of the graphics screen:
<XMP>
<HP2>
         MACRO POST
         FORTRAN/FILE 66 PAW.PS
         META -66 -111
         PICT/PLOT ' '
         CLOSE 66
         SHELL PRINT PAW.PS
         RETURN
</HP2>
</XMP>
By typing <XPH>EXEC POST</XPH> the current HPLOT picture on the
screen will be sent to the printer via the <XPH>SHELL</XPH> command
which send to the local operating system the system-dependent
<HP2>print</HP2> command
(e.g. <XPH><HP2>prf -trans -pr lw</HP2></XPH> on APOLLO).
<P>Other available commands working on pictures in memory are:
<XMP>
<I1>PICTURE/RENAME
<I1>PICTURE/COPY
<I1>PICTURE/DELETE
PAW > <HP3>PICT/RENAME PNAME PNAME2</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>PICT/COPY PNAME PNAME2</HP3>
PAW > <HP3>PICT/DELETE PNAME</HP3>
</XMP>
<UL>
<LI>PNAME can be the complete name, the picture number in memory or '&nbsp;'.
<LI>PNAME2 is the complete picture name.
</UL>
<H3>Pictures in direct access files
<P>HIGZ pictures are stored in direct-access files and hence
access times to pictures are fast. Moreover, due to the fact that
HIGZ uses high level primitives to describe the picture's structural
tree, a storage compaction factor as compared to the equivalent
GKS metafiles of between <XPH>10</XPH> and <XPH>100</XPH>
is routinely obtained.
<P>As HIGZ is interfaced to various basic graphics packages, a picture
file can be created with one system (e.g. DECGKS) and transported to
another machine to be interpreted with a different graphics package
(e.g GKSGRAL or DI3000).
<P>All available commands to handle pictures in ZEBRA files are shown below.
Note that in the example the picture names could be '<XPH>*</XPH>',
'&nbsp;' or a number.
<XMP SCALE=0.95>
&nbsp;
PAW > * Open an existing picture file PICT.DAT on LUN 4 in Update mode
PAW > <HP3>PICT/FILE 4 PICT.DAT ! U</HP3>  | Open the existing file PICT.DAT
PAW > <HP3>LDIR</HP3>                      | List the content of the file PICT.DAT
 
